[{"id":"VR106315","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VR106292.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The cities of Edmonton and Calgary are relatively far north and at high elevation. Which of the following best explains the data presented in their ecological footprints?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR106315_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a stacked bar graph titled “Average Per Capita Ecological Footprint of Major Canadian Cities from 2010 through 2015.” The horizontal axis is labeled “City,” and the following 6 cities are indicated: Charlottetown, Halifax, Montreal, Ottawa, Calgary, and Edmonton. Each city has one bar of data which is divided into 5 sections that represent services, goods, personal transportation, housing, and food. The vertical axis is labeled “Ecological Footprint per Capita, in global hectares,” and the values 0 through 10 are indicated. The data represented by the bars are as follows. Note that all values are approximate. Charlottetown: Food, 1.1; Housing, 0.5; Personal Transportation, 1.5; Goods, 0.6; Services, 0.3; total, 4 global hectares. Halifax: Food, 1.2; Housing, 3.5; Personal Transportation, 1.6; Goods, 0.8; Services, 0.4; total, 7.5 global hectares. Montreal: Food, 1.3; Housing, 0.5; Personal Transportation, 1.4; Goods, 0.7; Services, 0.4; total, 4.3 global hectares. Ottawa: Food, 1.0; Housing, 0.7; Personal Transportation, 1.1; Goods, 0.3; Services, 0.4; total, 3.5 global hectares. Calgary: Food, 1.3; Housing, 4.5; Personal Transportation, 2.2; Goods, 0.7; Services, 0.5; total, 9.2 global hectares. Edmonton: Food, 1.2; Housing, 3.7; Personal Transportation, 2.1; Goods, 0.6; Services, 0.5; total, 8.1 global hectares.\" height=\"247\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR106292.g08.png\" width=\"560\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Many of the inhabitants of Edmonton and Calgary must commute to southern cities for work.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Products must be shipped large distances from major shipping ports to Edmonton and Calgary.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Growing seasons are shorter in Edmonton and Calgary, requiring larger amounts of fertilizers to grow crops.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Colder average temperatures and longer nights in Edmonton and Calgary lead to high energy usage to heat and light homes.</p>"],"answer":3}]